    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The High-Tech ID</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Henry Elkins letter says use of false birth certificates by illegal immigrants (May 29 article) points up the need for more accurate system of identification</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''False Birth Certificates Let Immigrants Outwit System'' (news article, May 29):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''False Birth Certificates Let Immigrants Outwit System'' (news article, May 29):</p>
        <p>The remedies suggested by the Commission on Immigration Reform for false birth certificates -- single certificate design, matching births and deaths, standardized application forms, computerized storage of birth records -- are worthy but superficial remedies for a much larger problem of inaccurate identification of our citizenry.</p>
        <p>Fair administration of immigration laws, meaningful gun control and effective criminal justice require accurate identification based on one or more physical attributes, be they DNA, retinal or digital. Photographs, birth dates and credit card numbers do not suffice.</p>
        <p>HENRY ELKINS  Bronxville, N.Y., May 30, 2000</p>
      </block>
